===Etymology===
From {{inh|en|enm|welcome}}, {{m|enm|wolcume}}, {{m|enm|wulcume}}, {{m|enm|wilcume}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{m|ang|wilcuma}} {{gloss|"one whose coming is pleasant, a welcome person or thing, a guest"; compare also {{m|ang|wilcume||welcome!|pos=interjection}}}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*wiljakwumô||a comer, a welcomed guest}}, equivalent to {{compound|will|t1=desire|come|t2=comer, arrival|lang=en}}. Cognate with {{cog|sco|walcome||welcome}}, {{cog|fy|wolkom||welcome}}, {{cog|nl|welkom||welcome}}, {{cog|de|willkommen||welcome}}, Danish and Norwegian {{m|da|velkommen||welcome}}, Swedish {{m|sv|välkommen||welcome}}, {{cog|is|velkomin||welcome}}, Low Saxon: ''walkommen''.

Similar constructions are common in [[Romance languages]], such as Italian {{m|it|benvenuto}}, Spanish {{m|es|bienvenido}}, French {{m|fr|bienvenue}}, Catalan {{m|ca|benvingut}}, Portuguese {{m|pt|bem-vindo}} and Romanian {{m|ro|bun venit}}, each meaning “[may you have fared] well [in] coming [here]”. These do not derive from Classic Latin, where a similar construction is not found, and presumably are instead the result of a calque from Germanic to Proto-Romance (Vulgar Latin).

